n the Interval of the Wave is a close study of diaries written by Prince Edward Island women in the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. Women from both rural and urban regions of the Island recorded their lives in a genre that allowed them to play with the conventions of the language they knew. For busy farm wives, their "idian language, syntax, and choice of topic appear simple, whereas for the urban elite like Margaret Gray Lord and Wanda Wyatt, the erudition of their diaries suggests a more leisured existence. Mary McDonald-Rissanen argues that the initial reception of the text - its physical appearance, handwriting, gaps, and flood of words - provides interesting insights for understanding the circumstances of Prince Edward Island women from times past. Intertextual readings of the diaries alongside other cultural artifacts such as paintings, histories, folk stories, and songs embellish the idiosyncratic diary discourse. Diaries enabled women to write their voices, create a subjective identity, and redefine their place in the world. In the Interval of the Wave exposes lives lived and recorded in a special moment and place never far from the rhythm of the sea.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWomen and literaturexHistoryx19th centuryxPrince Edward Island. 0aWomen and literaturexHistoryx20th centuryxPrince Edward Island. 0aWomen and literaturezPrince Edward IslandxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen and literaturezPrince Edward IslandxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen authors, CanadianxDiariesxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen authors, CanadianzPrince Edward IslandxBiographyxHistory and criticism. 0aWomenxBiographyxPrince Edward Island. 0aWomenxHistoryx19th centuryxPrince Edward Island. 0aWomenxHistoryx20th centuryxPrince Edward Island. 0aWomenxIdentityxPrince Edward Island. 0aWo